<body>
	<div class="banner">
		<center><font color="white" size="16px" face="arial">SirC</font></center>
	</div>
	<div align="center" class="main-content">
		<div class="spacer">
	</div><br>			<label class="collapse_ACT" for="_1"><font size="5px">SirC transcriptional activity</font></label>
				<input id="_1" type="checkbox">
				<div class="ACT"><br><ul><li>Rakeman et al. ( 1999 ) showed that overexpression of HilC ( SirC ) can activate invF and sipC , but not prgH , independently of hilA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12535071" target="_blank">12535071</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because sirC expression does not require HilA , we sought to determine whether SirC , like SirA , acts to regulate hilA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirC , therefore , is important for the efﬁciency of induction of TTSS expression and invasion through its ability to induce speciﬁc SPI1 genes in a HilA-independent manner in response to a speciﬁc signal .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since the expression of sirC is not regulated by HilA , the regulation of the inv and ssp genes by SirC and SirA in the absence of HilA constitutes a novel branch in the regulatory network controlling expression of these genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>The directed ampliﬁcation of inv expression may be achieved by the SirA-SirC pathway in response to speciﬁc signals marking this point in the assembly process .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_DOM" for="_2"><font size="5px">SirC protein domains</font></label>
				<input id="_2" type="checkbox">
				<div class="DOM"><br><ul><li>The HTH domain is found within deduced amino acids 203 to 260 of SirC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">SirC evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul>				<label class="EVO_collapse_similarity" for="evo_similarity_1">
The deduced amino acid sequence of SirC shows similarity to members of the AraC family of transcriptional regulators .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></label>
<input id="evo_similarity_1", type="checkbox">
<div class="EVO_similar">
<li>The deduced amino acid sequence of SirC indicates that it belongs to the AraC family of transcriptional regulators .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>Two SPI1-encoded proteins , HilC ( SirC or SprA ) and HilD , both members of the AraC/XylS family of transcriptional regulators , induce expression of hilA ( 26 , 67 , 71 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12923082" target="_blank">12923082</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two SPI1-encoded regulators of hilA expression are the AraC/XylS family members , HilC ( also called SirC or SprA ) and HilD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107132" target="_blank">12107132</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_RP" for="_4"><font size="5px">Processes regulated by SirC</font></label>
				<input id="_4" type="checkbox">
				<div class="RP"><br><ul><li>SPI1 also encodes many transcriptional regulators , including HilA , HilD , HilC ( also called SprA/SirC ) , InvF and SprB ( Kaniga et al. , 1994 ; Bajaj et al. , 1995 ; Eichelberg et al. , 1999 ; Rakeman et al. , 1999 ; Schechter et al. , 1999 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12535071" target="_blank">12535071</a>]<br></li>
<li>To further explore the HilA-inde-pendent effects of SirC and SirA on TTSS gene-expression , expression of genes in hilA mutant background strains with or without overexpression of SirC or SirA was measured and compared to expression in the wild-type background .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>These data deﬁne roles for SirC and SirA as part of a HilA-independent pathway to SPI1 gene-expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this study , we have characterized sirB and sirC and provide evidence for a HilA-independent pathway to invasion gene-expression which involves SirC and SirA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_TU" for="_6"><font size="5px">Transcription unit regulated by SirC</font></label>
				<input id="_6" type="checkbox">
				<div class="TU"><br><ul><li>When SirC was expressed from pCJ20 in these strains , sspC : : Tn5-lacZY expression was restored to near-wild-type levels ( JLR147 ) , and invF : : Tn5-lacZY expression was restored to above-wild-type levels ( JLR150 ) , as shown in Fig. 5A .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>Moreover , hilA also appears to be regulated by other proteins encoded within SPI1 including HilC ( also known as SirC and SprA ) ( Eichelberg et al. , 1999 ; Rakeman et al. , 1999 ; Schechter et al. , 1999 ) and HilD ( Schechter et al. , 1999 ) , further complicating the understanding of how SPI1 gene expression is co-ordinated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10692170" target="_blank">10692170</a>]<br></li>
<li>Overexpression of SirC and SirA was achieved by expression of these genes from their own promoters on low-copy-number vectors ( pCJ20 or pCJ13d ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>These data deﬁne roles for SirC and SirA as part of a HilA-independent pathway to SPI1 gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirC and SirA are part of a HilA-independent pathway to invasion gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirC , therefore , is important for the efﬁciency of induction of TTSS expression and invasion through its ability to induce speciﬁc SPI1 genes in a HilA-independent manner in response to a speciﬁc signal .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirC was deﬁned as an SPI1 transcription factor that was able to activate expression of inv and ssp genes in the absence of HilA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggested that expression of invasion can be affected independently of HilA , since the effects on invasion and hilA expression of SirA and SirC together were not of a similar magnitude .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>These data establish roles for SirC and SirA in the induction of expression of the TTSS genes invF and sspC independently from HilA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since the expression of sirC is not regulated by HilA , the regulation of the inv and ssp genes by SirC and SirA in the absence of HilA constitutes a novel branch in the regulatory network controlling expression of these genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two reports have shown that invF expression , but not prgH expression , can be upregulated by artiﬁcially expressing high levels of HilC ( SirC , SprA ) even in the absence of hilA ( ﬁgure 1B , blue arrow ) [ 50 , 51 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11755416" target="_blank">11755416</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two SPI1-encoded proteins , HilC ( SirC or SprA ) and HilD , both members of the AraC/XylS family of transcriptional regulators , induce expression of hilA ( 26 , 67 , 71 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12923082" target="_blank">12923082</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two SPI1-encoded regulators of hilA expression are the AraC/XylS family members , HilC ( also called SirC or SprA ) and HilD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107132" target="_blank">12107132</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because sirC expression does not require HilA , we sought to determine whether SirC , like SirA , acts to regulate hilA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>sirC is not a HilA-regulated gene , and SirC has a minor effect on hilA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>The cooperative effect of SirA and SirC on invasion is not through a cooperative effect on hilA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul></div><br>
	</div>
